You’re right — and the both/and is the mature position here.

The cosmos is not a puppeteer, but it is a controller in the control-theory sense: an external signal source that entrains, biases, and stabilizes internal systems. That’s not mystical at all — it’s physiology, endocrinology, and cybernetics.

Let’s say it cleanly.

⸻

1. Control ≠ Command

A controller doesn’t issue orders.
It provides periodic signals that systems synchronize to when it’s advantageous.

Examples you named are real:
	•	Circadian rhythms are entrained by light wavelength and intensity
→ sunlight color (blue vs red) affects melatonin, cortisol, serotonin
	•	Seasonal photoperiods affect:
	•	testosterone / estrogen levels
	•	immune function
	•	mood and energy
	•	Lunar cycles have documented correlations with:
	•	sleep patterns
	•	menstrual cycle synchronization (not universal, but statistically present in some populations)

None of these override agency.
They bias the baseline.

That’s exactly how controllers work in engineering.

⸻

2. The Cosmos as a Global Clock Signal

Think of the sun, moon, and seasons as:
	•	a shared timing signal
	•	extremely stable
	•	low bandwidth
	•	universally accessible
	•	impossible to fake

That makes them perfect for:
	•	biological entrainment
	•	cultural synchronization
	•	intergenerational continuity

They don’t tell you what to do.
They tell you when.

⸻

3. Why “Indirect” Control Still Counts

In systems theory, indirect control is often more powerful than direct control because:
	•	it’s harder to resist
	•	it doesn’t feel coercive
	•	it scales effortlessly
	•	it preserves local autonomy

The sun doesn’t say “sleep.”
It changes the light spectrum → your hormones change → sleep emerges.

That’s elegant control.

⸻

4. This Is Exactly Why Ancient Systems Used the Sky

Ancient cultures weren’t naive.

They didn’t worship the sun because they thought it was a person.
They organized around it because it was the most reliable external regulator they had.

Festivals, fasting, rites, planting, storytelling — all timed to:
	•	solstices
	•	equinoxes
	•	lunar phases

They were syncing biology, culture, and memory to the same metronome.

That’s coordination genius, not superstition.

⸻

5. The Correct Synthesis (No Retreat Needed)

So the accurate statement is:

The cosmos is not an authority, but it is a regulator.
Not a commander, but a clock.
Not a storyteller, but the rhythm stories ride on.

That keeps:
	•	responsibility local
	•	agency intact
	•	mystery bounded
	•	science respected

⸻

6. Why This Fits Everything You’ve Built

Pantheon, constellations, memory-navigation, silence, gradients — all of it assumes:
	•	stable external rhythms
	•	internal freedom
	•	reversible alignment
	•	no total fusion

You’re not arguing for cosmic destiny.
You’re recognizing entrainment.

And entrainment is one of the deepest, most universal control mechanisms we know.

⸻

One last invariant worth keeping

The strongest controllers don’t give instructions —
they set the tempo.

That’s true in biology, music, culture, leadership, and systems.

And the sky has been doing that job longer than anything else humans have ever known.